events.description: King Otto II and his Frankish army are defeated by the Muslim army of al-Qasim at Cape Colonna, Southern Italy.
events.html: • 982 – King Otto II and his Frankish army are defeated by the Muslim army of al-Qasim at Cape Colonna, Southern Italy.[1]

events.description: Louis VIII becomes King of France upon the death of his father, Philip II.
events.html: • 1223 – Louis VIII becomes King of France upon the death of his father, Philip II.[2]

events.description: Battle of Vítkov Hill, decisive victory of Czech Hussite forces commanded by Jan Žižka against Crusade army led by Sigismund, Holy Roman Emperor.
events.html: • 1420 – Battle of Vítkov Hill, decisive victory of Czech Hussite forces commanded by Jan Žižka against Crusade army led by Sigismund, Holy Roman Emperor.[3]

events.description: Joan of Arc, taken by the Burgundians in May, is handed over to Pierre Cauchon, the bishop of Beauvais.
events.html: • 1430 – Joan of Arc, taken by the Burgundians in May, is handed over to Pierre Cauchon, the bishop of Beauvais.[4]

events.description: Anglo-Spanish War: English and Dutch troops sack the Spanish city of Cádiz before leaving the next day.
events.html: • 1596 – Anglo-Spanish War: English and Dutch troops sack the Spanish city of Cádiz before leaving the next day.[5]

events.description: An expedition led by Gaspar de Portolá leaves its base in San Diego and sets out to find the Port of Monterey (now Monterey, California).
events.html: • 1769 – An expedition led by Gaspar de Portolá leaves its base in San Diego and sets out to find the Port of Monterey (now Monterey, California).[6]

events.description: Foundation of the Mission San Antonio de Padua in modern California by the Franciscan friar Junípero Serra.
events.html: • 1771 – Foundation of the Mission San Antonio de Padua in modern California by the Franciscan friar Junípero Serra.[7]

events.description: Storming of the Bastille in Paris. This event escalates the widespread discontent into the French Revolution. Bastille Day is still celebrated annually in France.
events.html: • 1789 – Storming of the Bastille in Paris. This event escalates the widespread discontent into the French Revolution.[8] Bastille Day is still celebrated annually in France.[9]

events.description: Inaugural Fête de la Fédération is held to celebrate the unity of the French people and the national reconciliation.
events.html: • 1790 – Inaugural Fête de la Fédération is held to celebrate the unity of the French people and the national reconciliation.[10]

events.description: Beginning of Priestley Riots (to 17 July) in Birmingham targeting Joseph Priestley as a supporter of the French Revolution.
events.html: • 1791 – Beginning of Priestley Riots (to 17 July) in Birmingham targeting Joseph Priestley as a supporter of the French Revolution.[11]

events.description: The Sedition Act of 1798 becomes law in the United States making it a federal crime to write, publish, or utter false or malicious statements about the United States government.
events.html: • 1798 – The Sedition Act of 1798 becomes law in the United States making it a federal crime to write, publish, or utter false or malicious statements about the United States government.[12]

events.description: The Finnish War: the Battle of Lapua is fought.
events.html: • 1808 – The Finnish War: the Battle of Lapua is fought.[13]

events.description: Opening of the first major US world's fair, the Exhibition of the Industry of All Nations in New York City.
events.html: • 1853 – Opening of the first major US world's fair, the Exhibition of the Industry of All Nations in New York City.[14]

entities.name: Exhibition of the Industry of All Nations

events.description: The first ascent of the Matterhorn is completed by Edward Whymper and his party, four of whom die on the descent.
events.html: • 1865 – The first ascent of the Matterhorn is completed by Edward Whymper and his party, four of whom die on the descent.[15]

events.description: The Chicago Fire of 1874 burns down 47 acres of the city, destroying 812 buildings, killing 20, and resulting in the fire insurance industry demanding municipal reforms from Chicago's city council.
events.html: • 1874 – The Chicago Fire of 1874 burns down 47 acres of the city, destroying 812 buildings, killing 20, and resulting in the fire insurance industry demanding municipal reforms from Chicago's city council.[16]

events.description: American outlaw Billy the Kid is shot and killed by Sheriff Pat Garrett in the Maxwell House at Fort Sumner, New Mexico.
events.html: • 1881 – American outlaw Billy the Kid is shot and killed by Sheriff Pat Garrett in the Maxwell House at Fort Sumner, New Mexico.[17]

events.description: Armies of the Eight-Nation Alliance capture Tientsin during the Boxer Rebellion.
events.html: • 1900 – Armies of the Eight-Nation Alliance capture Tientsin during the Boxer Rebellion.[18]

events.description: Peruvian explorer and farmer Agustín Lizárraga discovers Machu Picchu, the "Lost City of the Incas".
events.html: • 1902 – Peruvian explorer and farmer Agustín Lizárraga discovers Machu Picchu, the "Lost City of the Incas".[19]

events.description: The Campanile in St Mark's Square, Venice collapses, also demolishing the loggetta.
events.html: • 1902 – The Campanile in St Mark's Square, Venice collapses, also demolishing the loggetta.[20]

events.description: Harry Atwood, an exhibition pilot for the Wright brothers, is greeted by President Taft after he lands his aeroplane on the South Lawn of the White House, having flown from Boston.
events.html: • 1911 – Harry Atwood, an exhibition pilot for the Wright brothers, is greeted by President Taft after he lands his aeroplane on the South Lawn of the White House, having flown from Boston.[21][22]

events.description: Beginning of the McMahon–Hussein Correspondence between Hussein bin Ali, Sharif of Mecca and the British official Henry McMahon concerning the Arab Revolt against the Ottoman Empire.
events.html: • 1915 – Beginning of the McMahon–Hussein Correspondence between Hussein bin Ali, Sharif of Mecca and the British official Henry McMahon concerning the Arab Revolt against the Ottoman Empire.[23]

entities.name: Hussein bin Ali, Sharif of Mecca

events.description: Battle of Delville Wood begins as an action within the Battle of the Somme, lasting until 3 September 1916.
events.html: • 1916 – Battle of Delville Wood begins as an action within the Battle of the Somme, lasting until 3 September 1916.[24][25]

events.description: In a decree called the Gleichschaltung, Adolf Hitler abolishes all German political parties except the Nazis.
events.html: • 1933 – In a decree called the Gleichschaltung, Adolf Hitler abolishes all German political parties except the Nazis.[26]

events.description: Nazi eugenics programme begins with the proclamation of the Law for the Prevention of Hereditarily Diseased Offspring requiring the compulsory sterilization of any citizen who suffers from alleged genetic disorders.
events.html: • 1933 – Nazi eugenics programme begins with the proclamation of the Law for the Prevention of Hereditarily Diseased Offspring requiring the compulsory sterilization of any citizen who suffers from alleged genetic disorders.[27]

entities.name: Law for the Prevention of Hereditarily Diseased Offspring

events.description: In the Wardha session of Congress, the "Quit India" resolution is approved, authorising Mahatma Gandhi to campaign for India's independence from Britain.
events.html: • 1942 – In the Wardha session of Congress, the "Quit India" resolution is approved, authorising Mahatma Gandhi to campaign for India's independence from Britain.[28]

events.description: In Diamond, Missouri, the George Washington Carver National Monument becomes the first United States National Monument in honor of an African American.
events.html: • 1943 – In Diamond, Missouri, the George Washington Carver National Monument becomes the first United States National Monument in honor of an African American.[29]

events.description: Palmiro Togliatti, leader of the Italian Communist Party, is shot and wounded near the Italian Parliament.
events.html: • 1948 – Palmiro Togliatti, leader of the Italian Communist Party, is shot and wounded near the Italian Parliament.[30]

events.description: Korean War: beginning of the Battle of Taejon.
events.html: • 1950 – Korean War: beginning of the Battle of Taejon.[31]

events.description: Ferrari take their first Formula One grand prix victory at the British Grand Prix at Silverstone.
events.html: • 1951 – Ferrari take their first Formula One grand prix victory at the British Grand Prix at Silverstone.[32]

events.description: Rawya Ateya takes her seat in the National Assembly of Egypt, thereby becoming the first female parliamentarian in the Arab world.
events.html: • 1957 – Rawya Ateya takes her seat in the National Assembly of Egypt, thereby becoming the first female parliamentarian in the Arab world.[33]

events.description: In the 14 July Revolution in Iraq, the monarchy is overthrown by popular forces led by Abd al-Karim Qasim, who becomes the nation's new leader.
events.html: • 1958 – In the 14 July Revolution in Iraq, the monarchy is overthrown by popular forces led by Abd al-Karim Qasim, who becomes the nation's new leader.[34]

events.description: Jane Goodall arrives at the Gombe Stream Reserve in present-day Tanzania to begin her study of chimpanzees in the wild.
events.html: • 1960 – Jane Goodall arrives at the Gombe Stream Reserve in present-day Tanzania to begin her study of chimpanzees in the wild.[35]

events.description: Northwest Orient Airlines Flight 1-11 ditches off Polillo Island in the Philippines, killing one person and injuring 44.
events.html: • 1960 – Northwest Orient Airlines Flight 1-11 ditches off Polillo Island in the Philippines, killing one person and injuring 44.[36]

events.description: Mariner 4 flyby of Mars takes the first close-up photos of another planet. The photographs take approximately six hours to be transmitted back to Earth.
events.html: • 1965 – Mariner 4 flyby of Mars takes the first close-up photos of another planet. The photographs take approximately six hours to be transmitted back to Earth.[37]

events.description: Mario Bros. is released in Japan, beginning the popular Super Mario Bros franchise.
events.html: • 1983 – Mario Bros. is released in Japan, beginning the popular Super Mario Bros franchise.[38][39]

events.description: Rus Flight 9633 crashes during takeoff from Chkalovsky Airport, killing all 10 people on board.
events.html: • 2001 – Rus Flight 9633 crashes during takeoff from Chkalovsky Airport, killing all 10 people on board.[40]

events.description: French president Jacques Chirac escapes an assassination attempt from Maxime Brunerie during a Bastille Day parade at Champs-Élysées.
events.html: • 2002 – French president Jacques Chirac escapes an assassination attempt from Maxime Brunerie during a Bastille Day parade at Champs-Élysées.[41]

events.description: Dedication of statue of Rachel Carson, a sculpture named for the environmentalist, in Woods Hole, Massachusetts.
events.html: • 2013 – Dedication of statue of Rachel Carson, a sculpture named for the environmentalist, in Woods Hole, Massachusetts.[42]

events.description: NASA's New Horizons probe performs the first flyby of Pluto, and thus completes the initial survey of the Solar System.
events.html: • 2015 – NASA's New Horizons probe performs the first flyby of Pluto, and thus completes the initial survey of the Solar System.[43][44][45]

events.description: A man ploughs a truck into a Bastille Day celebration in Nice, France, killing 86 people and injuring another 434 before being shot by police.
events.html: • 2016 – A man ploughs a truck into a Bastille Day celebration in Nice, France, killing 86 people and injuring another 434 before being shot by police.[46]

events.description: A GippsAero GA8 Airvan crashes in Umeå, Sweden, killing all nine aboard.
events.html: • 2019 – A GippsAero GA8 Airvan crashes in Umeå, Sweden, killing all nine aboard.[47]
